<aiml>

  <topic name="workouts">

    <!-- YES/NO: replying to "Do you like gym training?" -->
    <category>
      <pattern>YES</pattern>
      <that>Do you like gym training?</that>
      <template>
        Nice, I like gym training too.  
        Do you prefer FULL BODY sessions or a SPLIT routine?
      </template>
    </category>

    <category>
      <pattern>NO</pattern>
      <that>Do you like gym training?</that>
      <template>
        No worries. We can still plan simple bodyweight or running sessions.  
        Do you prefer FULL BODY training or a SPLIT routine?
      </template>
    </category>

    <!-- FULL BODY / SPLIT choice (no <that>, so they always work in this topic) -->
    <category>
      <pattern>FULL BODY</pattern>
      <template>
        Ok, FULL BODY it is.  
        <condition name="level">
          <li value="beginner">
            For a beginner full body routine, try 3 sessions per week:
            squats, push ups or bench press, rows, and planks.
          </li>
          <li value="intermediate">
            For an intermediate full body routine, 3 to 4 sessions per week
            with heavier squats, bench press, rows, and some isolation work.
          </li>
          <li value="advanced">
            As an advanced trainee, you can still use full body 3 times per week
            with heavier compound lifts and some extra volume.
          </li>
          <li>
            I do not know your level yet. Tell me by saying:
            "I am a beginner", "I am an intermediate", or "I am advanced".
          </li>
        </condition>
        If you want a short summary based only on your level, say: "GIVE ME A WORKOUT".
      </template>
    </category>

    <category>
      <pattern>SPLIT</pattern>
      <template>
        Ok, SPLIT it is.  
        <condition name="level">
          <li value="beginner">
            As a beginner, a simple upper and lower body split
            3 to 4 days per week is enough.
          </li>
          <li value="intermediate">
            As an intermediate trainee, an upper/lower split or push/pull/legs
            across 4 days per week works well.
          </li>
          <li value="advanced">
            As an advanced trainee, a push/pull/legs style split
            over 5 days per week can give you more volume.
          </li>
          <li>
            I do not know your level yet. Tell me by saying:
            "I am a beginner", "I am an intermediate", or "I am advanced".
          </li>
        </condition>
        If you want a short summary based only on your level, say: "GIVE ME A WORKOUT".
      </template>
    </category>

    <!-- Main workout suggestion based on level only -->
    <category>
      <pattern>GIVE ME A WORKOUT</pattern>
      <template>
        <condition name="level">
          <li value="beginner">
            For your level, you can try: 3 full body sessions per week
            with light weights and focus on technique.
          </li>
          <li value="intermediate">
            For your level, you can try: 4 training days per week
            with an upper/lower split.
          </li>
          <li value="advanced">
            For your level, you can try: 5 training days per week
            with a push/pull/legs style split.
          </li>
          <li>
            I do not know your level yet.
            Please say "I am a beginner", "I am an intermediate", or "I am advanced".
          </li>
        </condition>
        If you want to focus on one body part, say for example:
        "I WANT TO TRAIN LEGS".
      </template>
    </category>

    <!-- Too hard / too easy / another workout -->
    <category>
      <pattern>TOO HARD</pattern>
      <template>
        Ok, we can make it easier.  
        <condition name="level">
          <li value="beginner">
            For a beginner, drop one set per exercise and slow down the tempo.
          </li>
          <li value="intermediate">
            For an intermediate trainee, you can reduce volume slightly
            or keep the same plan with lighter weights.
          </li>
          <li value="advanced">
            Even advanced lifters have tough days. Reduce the weight and keep the structure.
          </li>
          <li>
            I do not know your level yet. Tell me your level first.
          </li>
        </condition>
        If you want, say "GIVE ME A WORKOUT" again for a short summary.
      </template>
    </category>

    <category>
      <pattern>THIS IS TOO HARD</pattern>
      <template>
        <srai>TOO HARD</srai>
      </template>
    </category>

    <category>
      <pattern>TOO EASY</pattern>
      <template>
        Good problem to have.  
        <condition name="level">
          <li value="beginner">
            If it feels too easy as a beginner, add a small amount of weight or one extra set.
          </li>
          <li value="intermediate">
            As an intermediate trainee, you can add volume or intensity gradually.
          </li>
          <li value="advanced">
            As an advanced trainee, you probably know your limits â€” add volume carefully and track fatigue.
          </li>
          <li>
            I do not know your level yet. Tell me your level first.
          </li>
        </condition>
        You can also say "GIVE ME A WORKOUT" for a quick baseline.
      </template>
    </category>

    <category>
      <pattern>GIVE ME ANOTHER WORKOUT</pattern>
      <template>
        I keep the same general structure, but you can swap exercises you do not like  
        for similar movements. Here is the summary again:  
        <srai>GIVE ME A WORKOUT</srai>
      </template>
    </category>

    <!-- Favourite exercise using STAR + THINK + SET/GET -->
    <category>
      <pattern>MY FAVOURITE EXERCISE IS *</pattern>
      <template>
        <think><set name="favexercise"><star/></set></think>
        <get name="favexercise"/> is a solid exercise.
        I will try to remember that.
      </template>
    </category>

    <category>
      <pattern>WHAT IS MY FAVOURITE EXERCISE</pattern>
      <template>
        <condition name="favexercise">
          <li>Your favourite exercise is <get name="favexercise"/>.</li>
          <li>You have not told me your favourite exercise yet.</li>
        </condition>
      </template>
    </category>

    <!-- Use SET of body parts -->
    <category>
      <pattern>I WANT TO TRAIN <set>bodypart</set></pattern>
      <template>
        That is a good choice to train.
        For <star/>, use the same sets and reps as in your level plan
        from "GIVE ME A WORKOUT".
      </template>
    </category>

    <!-- Shortcuts so "LEGS", "CHEST", "BACK" alone still work -->
    <category>
      <pattern>LEGS</pattern>
      <template>
        <srai>I WANT TO TRAIN LEGS</srai>
      </template>
    </category>

    <category>
      <pattern>CHEST</pattern>
      <template>
        <srai>I WANT TO TRAIN CHEST</srai>
      </template>
    </category>

    <category>
      <pattern>BACK</pattern>
      <template>
        <srai>I WANT TO TRAIN BACK</srai>
      </template>
    </category>

    <!-- Simple MAP usage for assignment -->
    <category>
      <pattern>TEST MAP *</pattern>
      <template>
        Map test result: <map name="level2plan"><star/></map>
      </template>
    </category>

    <!-- Default inside workouts topic -->
    <category>
      <pattern>*</pattern>
      <template>
        In workout mode you can say things like:
        "GIVE ME A WORKOUT",
        "FULL BODY",
        "SPLIT",
        "LEGS",
        or "MY FAVOURITE EXERCISE IS squats".
      </template>
    </category>

  </topic>

</aiml>

